<li>The two mutants of STM1697 lose interaction with stFlhD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the FlhD2C2 complex , the FlhC subunit bears a DNA-binding activity , while the FlhD * Corresponding author .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16952964" target="_blank">16952964</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="DOM_collapse_similarity" for="dom_similarity_4">
In the FlhD4C2 complex , the FlhC subunit exhibits a DNA-binding activity , while the FlhD subunit strengthens its DNA-binding speciﬁcity and stabilizes the protein-DNA complex ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21278297" target="_blank">21278297</a>]<br></label>
<input id="dom_similarity_4", type="checkbox">
<div class="DOM_similar">
<li>The FlhC subunit has DNA-binding activity , while the FlhD subunit strengthens its DNA-binding speciﬁcity and stabilizes the protein-DNA complex ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21278297" target="_blank">21278297</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Although the structure of the FlhD4C2 complex was recently solved in the absence of its DNA-binding site , 11 the authors proposed a model where each DNA half-site made two major contacts with an FlhD dimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18486950" target="_blank">18486950</a>]<br></li>
<li>In a model for FlhD4C2 binding , two contacts were formed between an FlhD dimer and each half-site in the DNA .11 Our data provides some support for this model since these two contacts formed with the DNA is similar to the two important segments identified by the mutagenesis data .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18486950" target="_blank">18486950</a>]<br></li>
<li>Residues located in the interface are shown in stick mode with different colors ( stFlhD : hotpink , mgFlhD : blue ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
<li>( A ) Schematic diagram of essential residues denoting molecular interactions between STM1697 or YdiV and FlhD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
<li>The peptide regions of STM1344 which interact with FlhD ( Li et al. , 2012 ) are underlined and the alpha helixes involved are speciﬁed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24127899" target="_blank">24127899</a>]<br></li>
<li>Of three phenylalanines in alpha helixes 6 , 7 and 8 interacting with FlhD ( Li et al. , 2012 ) , only the residue corresponding to F168 in alpha helix 7 is present in STM1697 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24127899" target="_blank">24127899</a>]<br></li>
<li>Speciﬁc amino acids of STM1344 which make molecular interactions with FlhD are in bold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24127899" target="_blank">24127899</a>]<br></li>
<li>To more precisely identify the binding site of STM1697 with FlhD , preliminary peptide array analysis of STM1697 comprised of immobilized 15-mer peptides with three amino acid offsets indicated three potential amino acid stretches interacting with FlhD ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24127899" target="_blank">24127899</a>]<br></li>
<li>STM1697 and STM1344 have distinct binding interfaces with FlhD As the amino acid sequence of the STM1344 interaction interface with FlhD is poorly conserved in STM1697 ( Fig. 2D ) , we wondered whether STM1697 interacts in a similar way with FlhD4C2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24127899" target="_blank">24127899</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , many amino acids of alpha helix 8 of STM1344 ( YdiV ) providing the major interaction interface with FlhD are not conserved in STM1697 ( Li et al. , 2012 ; Fig. 2D ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24127899" target="_blank">24127899</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to form YdiV3FlhD4C2 and YdiV4FlhD4C2 complexes , YdiV must enter the ring-like structure of FlhD4C2 , disrupting the interface between the central FlhD subunits .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
<li>This also suggests that the C terminus of FlhD may play a role in YdiV binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21278297" target="_blank">21278297</a>]<br></li>
<li>By sequence alignment , we found that the key residues ( Phe160 and Leu173 ) of STM1697 in the interactional surface are highly conserved across its orthologs , suggesting this binding interaction of STM1697 -- FlhD may be employed widely ( Figure 3D ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
<li>Detailed analysis showed that the conformation of FlhD from STM1697 -- FlhD was almost the same as the one from YdiV -- FlhD except the side chain deflection of essential residues ( Tyr14 and Lys26 ) located in the interface of STM1697 -- FlhD ( Figure 4C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
<li>Additionally , three proteins , STM1344 ( also named YdiV or RflP ) , STM1697 and FliT , were recently identified as negative regulators of flagellum in Salmonella by direct protein -- protein interactions : FliT binds to the FlhC subunit , and STM1344 and STM1697 interact with the FlhD subunit ( 17 -- 22 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
<li>Eleven residues of STM1697 ( Val115 , Leu116 , Leu136 , Val147 , Phe160 , Lys167 , Leu172 , Leu173 , Lys175 , His176 and Tyr180 ) directly participate in the interaction with FlhD , forming a close interface through hydrophobic and electrostatic interactions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">FlhD evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>The ﬂhDC operon is the sole one belonging to class 1 and encodes FlhD and FlhC , which assemble into an FlhD4C2 heterohexamer acting as an activator of class 2 operons ( 31 , 42 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results suggest that FlhC and FlhD belong to the small group of central regulators of cell physiology known as timing proteins ( Gottesman and Maurizi , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675803" target="_blank">12675803</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , although both belong to the EAL-like domain family , a variety of clues show that the molecular mechanism by which STM1697 interacts with FlhD and regulates flagellar gene expression is different from that of YdiV .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28973452" target="_blank">28973452</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
